<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920214-0151</DOCNO><DOCID>920214-0151.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor --   Our New Legal Ideal:   Blameless Perpetrator</HL><DATE>02/14/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11</SO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   If someone wants to know why it is hard to start or keep abusiness in the U.S., have them read Kevin Pritchett'sexcellent, if scary, Jan. 14 article &quot;Car-Rental Firms DecryVicarious Blame.&quot; When carried to the extremes noted in thearticle, this concept not only stifles the creation ofbusiness but could ruin a small- to medium-sized firm.   If I had been a judge deciding the Alamo lawsuit cited, Iwould have found that the estate of the sailor driving the(wrecked) car owed Alamo for a new vehicle. There would havebeen no payment from Alamo to anyone. After reading thecomments from the theory's proponents, trial lawyers (what asurprise), I wonder if I am the one who has lost touch withreality.</LP><TEXT>   I suppose that this finding by the jury merely confirmsthe growing belief that no one is responsible for his or herown actions. This tendency has proved itself dangerous notonly in the business world, but also in the actions ofcriminals who continue to successfully portray themselves asvictims.   Robert M. Woolsey   Cedar Hill, Texas</TEXT></DOC>